|Label Position = left
}}

'''Maekawa Shrine''' (前川神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|神社}} located in {{ill|Kawaguchi, Saitama|en|川口市}}, Saitama Prefecture.

== Deities ==
The main hall enshrines the deities known as {{ill|Munakata Sanjojin|en|宗像三女神}}, specifically:
* {{ill|Tagitsuhime|en|多岐都比売命}}
* {{ill|Tagirihime|en|多紀理毘売命}}
* {{ill|Sayoirihime|en|狭依毘売命}}

The associated shrine houses:
* {{ill|Amaterasu|en|天照大御神}}
* {{ill|Sarutahiko|en|猿田彦神}}
* {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|en|菅原道真}}

== History ==
The exact year of the shrine’s foundation is unknown due to the destruction of its original records and buildings in a {{ill|Lightning strike|en|落雷}} fire on July 15, 1512.

The deity statues were originally enshrined in {{ill|Bunzō Village|en|文蔵村}}, now part of {{ill|Minami-ku, Saitama|en|南区 (さいたま市)}}. However, following a flood, the statues were carried by the waters and stopped in the present location, where a shrine was built and initially named "Sekijinja" (堰神社). It was later renamed "Sekisha" (勢貴社). 

In 1873, the shrine became a village shrine of Maekawa Village. It incorporated several smaller shrines, including Shimazaike Shinmeisha and Sannosha. In 1965, it was renamed "Maekawa Shrine." On April 5, 1978, its inner main hall (内本殿) was designated as a cultural property by Kawaguchi City.<ref>[http://www.city.kawaguchi.lg.jp/kbn/Files/1/01050038/attach/P30-31.pdf Kawaguchi City Newsletter 2014, p.31]</ref>

The ''{{ill|Shinpen Musashi Fudoki Kō|en|新編武蔵風土記稿}}'' describes Maekawa Shrine as follows: "Sekimei Shrine, enshrining Tagitsuhime no Mikoto, established for protection against flooding."

== Festivals ==
The main festival is held annually on October 17.<ref>[http://www.saitama-jinjacho.or.jp/shrine/8864/ Saitama Prefecture Shrine Bureau - Maekawa Shrine]</ref>

== References ==
{{Reflist}}

== External Links ==
* [https://www.maekawajinja.com/ Maekawa Shrine] - Official Website
* {{Twitter|MaekawaJinja_SK}}

